{"type":"message","id":"29d3011e","parentId":"41740583","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:03:39.166Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The remote server is responding with 401, which means the endpoint exists and is working. So the 404 in the browser is NOT from the remote server.\n\nThe issue must be that the FE is calling localhost:5002 (which is the local BE) but the local BE is not running. Wait - the local BE IS running on port 5002.\n\nActually, the 404 might be a browser-specific issue. The browser is getting a 404 from somewhere. Let me think about this...\n\nWait - maybe the issue is that when the FE runs in the browser, `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` is NOT set correctly. In Next.js, `NEXT_PUBLIC_` variables are baked into the build at compile time. \n\nSo the FE was built before `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` was added to `.env.local`, which means the production build is still pointing to `http://127.0.0.1:5002/api/v1` instead of the actual server URL. The fix is to rebuild the frontend to pick up the new environment variable, then redeploy. But I'm also noticing the remote server at 103.253.21.139:5002 returns a 401 for the license-categories endpoint, which means that route does exist on the remote, so this 404 isn't coming from there.\n\nWait, a 401 Unauthorized is different from a 404 Not Found — the server is actually responding, just requiring authentication. The browser might be getting a 404 from a CDN or proxy in front of the backend that's blocking or misrouting the request, or the NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL wasn't properly baked into the build.\n\nThe real solution is probably to rebuild and redeploy the frontend so the environment variable gets embedded correctly.","thinkingSignature":"61692d43edbec95481985d376c2e6a76645a737dd624845b19d971c555a2c8f9"},{"type":"text","text":"Remote BE trả `401` (endpoint tồn tại). Vấn đề nằm ở **FE build cũ chưa có `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`** trong code.\n\nKiểm tra:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_functio