{"type":"message","id":"36418aa8","parentId":"c1154e11","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:04:09.171Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` in the CI variables. So the CI build uses the default `http://127.0.0.1:5002/api/v1` which is hardcoded in the fallback. That can't be the cause of the 404 since 127.0.0.1:5002 returns 401 not 404.Wait - the remote backend at `http://103.253.21.139:5002` is also returning 401 (endpoint exists). So why is the browser getting 404?Maybe the browser simply can't reach the remote server due to network/firewall issues, and the browser returns 404 (not the server). Or maybe there's a reverse proxy (nginx) in front of the backend that returns 404 for unknown routes.Actually, I think the most likely issue is: the GitLab CI builds the Next.js app with `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` from the CI environment variables. Since it's not set, it uses the fallback. But the actual production URL should be set in the environment where the Next.js app runs. If the deployed Next.js app is at `http://103.253.21.139:3000`, it would call `http://127.0.0.1:5002/api/v1/...` from the browser, which would fail.\n\nSo the real problem is that `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` needs to be set as a CI/CD variable in GitLab, and I should check if there's a Docker configuration or deployment script where this environment variable can be properly configured.","thinkingSignature":"2dfc098f5a124fbb8a2cd4bc7dc64a4810cf51e714a0b62e500d00fc492be833"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qrk07azizd5u_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat Dockerfile 2>/dev/null | head -20","workdir":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces/teacher-driving-training-system.bootstrap-backup/ahv-qlhv-fe"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":124,"output":385,"cacheRead":97780,"cacheWrite":721,"totalTokens":99010,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","t